{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011vFeKe7Vgk8rP331jheU5W","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The baseline captured by the precondition is the same cert as what's in es-http-tls currently. There's no \"old\" cert that needs to be rotated based on what I see. But the task says \"certificates are nearing expiration\" and the task is to rotate them with new ones valid for about 1 year.\n\nLet me understand more about the actual state. The precondition captured the current CA cert. The task is to rotate certs. So I need to:\n\n1. Generate a new CA (valid for ~1 year)\n2. Generate a new leaf cert signed by the new CA (valid for ~1 year)\n3. Update the `es-http-tls` secret with the new certs\n4. Rolling restart of ES nodes to pick up the new certs\n\nThe key constraints are no ECK operator or CRDs, new certs valid for about a year, clients can trust the new CA, and minimal downtime. For the leaf cert SANs, I need to include localhost, the cluster name, individual node DNS names within the cluster, and the fully qualified domain names for each node in the Kubernetes service.\n\nFor minimal downtime, I should add the new CA to the trust bundle first so clients can trust both the old and new CAs, then rotate the leaf cert, and eventually remove the old CA once everything's stable. Since I'm doing this in one operation, I'll generate the new CA and leaf cert, update the secret with both the new leaf cert and a combined trust bundle containing both CAs, then do a rolling restart.\n\nLet me check how Elasticsearch actually configures TLS to make sure I understand which files go where—the `ca.crt` is what clients use to verify the server, while `tls.crt` and `tls.key` are the server's certificate and private key.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":191,"cache_read_input_tokens":31392,"cache_creation":{"ep