{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VS5xmG44VvTpMNvpTtTe6o","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now I understand the setup. The secret `es-http-tls` is mounted as a volume named `certs` in the StatefulSet. The certs are at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/`. \n\nThe Elasticsearch config uses both HTTP and transport TLS from the same cert/key pair. The `ca.crt` is used as the certificate authority for both transport and HTTP SSL.\n\nThe task is to rotate the HTTP CA and leaf certificates. The secret `es-http-tls` contains `ca.crt`, `tls.crt`, and `tls.key`.\nBut I'm realizing there's a constraint here—the same secret is used for both HTTP and transport TLS. If I rotate just the HTTP certificates, I need to ensure the transport layer keeps working since the config references the same cert files for both protocols.\n\nThe task is asking me to rotate the HTTP CA and leaf certificates, but since they're shared with transport, I'll need to rotate the entire shared certificate. For a 3-node cluster with minimal downtime, I should generate new CA and leaf certificates, then coordinate the rotation during a rolling update.\n\nActually, there's a complication here. If I swap the leaf certificate to one signed by a new CA while nodes still have the old CA cached, they won't be able to verify each other's certificates during the rolling restart. The safer approach is to do this in stages: first add the new CA alongside the old one so all nodes can trust both, then update the leaf certificate, then optionally clean up the old CA. That means multiple rolling restarts, but it ensures nodes can always communicate with each other.\n\nFor a test environment though, I can be more direct: generate the new CA and leaf cert, update the secret with both CAs concatenated in ca.crt and the new leaf cert, then do a rolling restart. The tricky part is that Kubernetes updates secret volumes automatically but Elasticsearch won't reload them—it only reads certs at startup, so the rolling restart is what actually picks up the new certificates.\n\nDuring the restart, nodes come up one at a time with the new cert signed by the new CA, while the remaining nodes still have the old CA in memory. This creates a problem for node-to-node communication: the restarted node presents a cert signed by the new CA, but the other nodes only trust the old CA and will reject it. The solution is a two-phase approach—first add the new CA to the trust store alongside the old one with a rolling restart, then in a second phase replace the leaf cert with the new one.\n\nSince Kubernetes automatically updates secret volumes, I can leverage this by updating the secret to include both CAs first, waiting for the volumes to sync across pods, then doing a rolling restart so all nodes trust both CAs. In the second phase, I update the secret again with the new leaf cert and key, then restart again so all nodes are serving the new cert while still trusting both CAs.\n\nBut I'm realizing the complexity here—Elasticsearch doesn't auto-reload certs from disk, so even if the files update, the in-memory CA that nodes loaded at startup won't change. This means during a rolling restart, earlier nodes that restart will have the new certs loaded, but nodes still running will only trust the old CA they loaded in memory, creating a trust mismatch.\n\nThe safe approach is a two-phase rolling restart: first update the CA bundle to include both old and new CAs while keeping the old leaf cert, so all nodes trust both CAs after restarting. Then in phase two, update to the new leaf cert signed by the new CA—now all nodes already trust it since they loaded both CAs in phase one.\n\nI should verify that Elasticsearch actually validates the CA chain with its `verification_mode: certificate` setting, which it does. Now let me check what the auth-checker pod is doing to understand the current state of things.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":319,"cache_read_input_tokens":33353,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":319},"output_tokens":38,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a4761880-da88-4c02-890d-4b0b4f77ac23","uuid":"5a8b5182-048a-4158-b3ca-ef77da9d0dc1","request_id":"req_011Ccg9LsZsCjr3LQqUV4gxD"}
